She seemed to grow increasingly suspicious in the scene, and by the end, it looked like she was even taking advantage of the situation.  I didn’t like or dislike her.  I have no real idea what was actually happening in that scene.  I don’t know.

gr1_qual.t1: He reminds me of a child.  Very naive, but good natured.  The way he darted his eyes back and forth when he began to understand that she was calling him the father exemplified my impression of him as naive.  It was carried farther through his need to be reassured that he didn’t do anything wrong.  But I thought it was good that he sat down with his son in an effort to get to know him.  I commend that.  Why did I dislike him more than I liked him?  I can’t be entirely sure, but he just seemed fragile or weak.  I don’t think I really understand why I felt that way.  And I feel kind of ashamed to express this.

gr1_qual.t1: To be honest, my feelings towards the character are influenced by my general antipathy that all movies are a vehicle for male fantasy. The females dreams, wishes wants etc are completely subordinate to that and used for that purpose only. So, basically, he is a disabled guy and with little effort has all these wonderful and great things happen in his life. She is of normal intelligence, but instead can hardly have a single normal thing work out in life and has terrible things happen to her. So, that it kinda is females are just evil and so deserve bad things? A normal female is not even worth half of a disabled guy in worth? As a female, there are things that just really rub me the wrong way. Ok, he got his girl, but she got knocked up and is a single mom with a disabled guy. Was that really her dream or wish and goal in life. But the movie is very well crafted in to not care or question that as the character Forest is so charismatic and pure and childlike and innocent that you are made to feel bad, for questioning it. So, in  a way, I dislike his "likability" as it is used for same overall propaganda and overall excuse of prejudice towards females and their "role" in life is to be supportive of the males goals and not to have or achieve their own. They they are "good" for that, but "bad" if they want something different. It is just a normalized sexist countries attitude and as it has caused real and huge harm to real females lives, I don't find the movie all that heartwarming.Can you even imagine a movie with a mentally disabled female gets a good looking and intelligent guy? And people think, wow that is so great and wonderful.Especially as part of the reason he is with her is that the world treats him like complete shit and so can't get any better? Imagine it reversed.

gr7_qual.t1: He seemed pretty ineffectual. I have no idea what circumstance led to the female character dying or how close the two characters were, but the way he dealt with her passing was very frail. It was like he didn't know how to act for her final moments. I did not feel much sympathy for his character. There's only so much you can do when interacting with someone who is about to die, but this character would be more heroic in my eyes if he reacted more bravely and strongly. Instead he wavered back and forth between what he was telling her, such as urging her not to look at what she was seeing (hallucinating), then letting it go almost immediately.
